    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about an escrow account for the closing and i'm kinda confused. what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the house purchase?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow is a neutral third-party account where funds and documents are held safely until the closing conditions are met, ensuring neither the buyer nor the seller gets ripped off. You need it to protect your money from being released to the seller until the title is clear, the deed is recorded, and all inspections and repairs are finalized. Without escrow, you'd be handing over your life savings to a stranger without any guarantee that the house is actually yours. It's a crucial safety net that prevents fraud and ensures a smooth transaction.\n\nIn the real estate world, escrow acts like a strict, rule-following guard who won't let the keys change hands until every single requirement is satisfied. If you skip this step, you risk losing your deposit or facing legal trouble if the seller tries to back out or if the title has hidden liens. Think of it as a specialized vault that only opens when both parties agree the deal is perfect.\n\nI can't help with the specific terms of your escrow agreement, but I can tell you that most buyers are required to have an escrow account to protect their funds during the transaction. It's not optional if you want to buy a home safely. If you're worried about the process, you should ask",
