      "content": "If a seller tries to grab money or hoard documents before the deal is done, the escrow officer is legally bound to freeze the funds immediately and refuse any premature release. They act as an impartial judge who will not let the seller touch a single cent until the buyer's conditions are fully satisfied. This strict adherence to the contract prevents the seller from \"hoarding\" the buyer's earnest money or other deposits, ensuring the funds remain in the escrow account until the final closing.\n\nIn the event of a dispute, the escrow officer will typically pause the closing process and notify both parties, often requiring them to resolve the issue through their attorneys or mediation before the transaction can proceed. If the seller acts in bad faith, the escrow company can be held liable, which is why they are so vigilant about following the exact terms of the agreement. It's a system designed to make it incredibly difficult for anyone to \"grab\" what isn't theirs.\n\nIf you suspect a specific issue with your current escrow agent, you should contact them directly or consult with your real estate attorney to ensure your funds are protected.",
